## Overview

This project compares the empirical power and Type I error of the Welch two-sample t-test and the Wilcoxon rank-sum test under several data-generating distributions. I used Monte Carlo simulation in R to evaluate how both tests perform when assumptions of normality hold and when they break down.

This study considers four distributional settings:

* Normal

* Right-skewed

* Heavy-tailed

* Uniform

Within each distribution, I varied sample size and effect size to examine how test performance changed across conditions.

In practice, analysts often compare two groups without knowing whether the underlying data are approximately normal. This simulation shows how test choice affects power and error control under realistic departures from normality.

## Research Questions

* When data are normally distributed, how much power does the t-test gain over the Wilcoxon test?

* How do both tests behave under skewed, heavy-tailed, and uniform distributions?

* Which test better maintains the nominal 0.05 Type I error rate under non-normal data?

* How do sample size and effect size change the gap between the two methods?

## Simulation Design

For each combination of distribution, sample size, and effect size, I generated two independent samples and applied both:

* Welch's two-sample t-test

* Wilcoxon rank-sum test

Each setting was simulated 10,000 times. Empirical power was estimated as the proportion of simulations in which the null hypothesis was rejected at $\alpha = 0.05$. When the effect size was set to 0, this proportion estimates empirical Type I error.

### Distributions

* Normal
	
* Exponential (right-skewed)
	
* t-distribution with 3 degrees of freedom (heavy-tailed)
	
* Uniform

### Sample Sizes

* n per group: 20, 50, 100

### Effect Sizes 

* $\delta$: 0, 0.2, 0.5, 1

## Tests Compared

The Welch t-test is designed to compare group means and is most efficient when data are approximately normal. The Wilcoxon rank-sum test is a nonparametric alternative based on ranks rather than raw values, which often makes it more robust to skewness, heavy tails, and outliers.

## Implementation

I wrote a reusable simulation function in R to generate paired samples under each distribution, apply both tests, and aggregate rejection rates across 10,000 repetitions per configuration. Results were stored in a combined data frame and visualized as power curves across effect sizes and sample sizes.

## Simulation Results

```{r simulate-all}

simulate_power <- function(n, dist_name, delta, reps = 10000){
  reject_t <- 0
  reject_w <- 0

  for (i in 1:reps){
    if (dist_name == "normal"){
      x <- rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = 1)
      y <- rnorm(n, mean = delta, sd = 1)
    } else if (dist_name == "exponential"){
      x <- rexp(n, rate = 1)
      y <- rexp(n, rate = 1) + delta
    } else if (dist_name == "heavy"){
      x <- rt(n, df = 3)
      y <- rt(n, df = 3) + delta
    } else if (dist_name == "uniform"){
      x <- runif(n, min = 0, max = 1)
      y <- runif(n, min = 0, max = 1) + delta
    }

    if (t.test(x, y, var.equal = FALSE)$p.value < 0.05){
      reject_t <- reject_t + 1
    }

    if (wilcox.test(x, y)$p.value < 0.05){
      reject_w <- reject_w + 1
    }
  }

  data.frame(
    dist = dist_name,
    n = n,
    delta = delta,
    test = c("Welch t-test", "Wilcoxon"),
    power = c(reject_t / reps, reject_w / reps)
  )
}

ns      <- c(20, 50, 100)
deltas  <- c(0, 0.2, 0.5, 1)
dists   <- c("normal", "exponential", "heavy", "uniform")

all_results <- list()
k <- 1

for (d in dists){
  for (n in ns){
    for (delta in deltas){
      all_results[[k]] <- simulate_power(n, d, delta, reps = 10000)
      k <- k + 1
    }
  }
}

results <- do.call(rbind, all_results)

```

