```

### Normal Data

Under normal sampling, the Welch t-test consistently achieved the highest power, especially at smaller effect sizes. The Wilcoxon test was slightly less powerful but remained competitive.

These results match theoretical expectations: the t-test is optimal under normality, while the Wilcoxon test sacrifices a small amount of efficiency.

### Right-Skewed Data

Under exponential sampling, the Wilcoxon test outperformed the t-test across most sample sizes and effect sizes. The t-test became less effective under skewness, while the rank-based Wilcoxon test remained more stable.

### Heavy-Tailed Data

For heavy-tailed data, the Wilcoxon test again showed higher power, particularly at smaller sample sizes. The t-test was more affected by the extreme values typical of heavy tailed data. As sample size increased, the performance gap narrowed, but Wilcoxon remained slightly more powerful.

### Uniform Data

Under the uniform distribution, both tests performed similarly. Differences were minor, suggesting that the Welch t-test remains reliable under mild non-normality when the distribution is still symmetric and bounded.

### Type I Error

When the true effect size was zero, both tests were expected to reject the null about 5% of the time. Across the simulated settings, the Wilcoxon test stayed closer to the nominal 0.05 level under skewed and heavy-tailed data, while the t-test showed mild inflation in some small-sample non-normal settings. This supports the idea that Wilcoxon is the more robust option when distribution assumptions are questionable.

### Key Takeaways

* The Welch t-test is most powerful when data are normally distributed.

* The Wilcoxon rank-sum test performs better under skewed and heavy-tailed data.

* Under symmetric but non-normal data, the two methods perform similarly.

* When distributional assumptions are uncertain, the Wilcoxon test provides a strong robust alternative.

